                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d206">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/3–1945: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-03-19T17:00:00+03:00"
                            >March 19, 1945—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 19—3:12 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>811. Sulzberger received his story from a source which he is pledged not to
                    reveal. From the way the Soviets (ReDeptel 566, March 12, <pb facs="0303"
                        n="293" xml:id="pg_293"/> 3 p.m.) operate I am quite sure that the story did
                    not come from a Russian source and I have reason to believe Sulzberger based his
                    story on information received from a foreign Embassy here.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
